  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I age a good Merlot?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality Merlots can age 8-15 years, with exceptional examples from Pomerol or premium California producers developing for 20+ years. The key factors are the wine's tannin structure, acidity levels, and concentration—wines with balanced acidity and sufficient extract age more gracefully. Most everyday Merlots are designed for consumption within 3-5 years of release, while reserve bottlings and Bordeaux Right Bank wines benefit from 5-10 years of cellaring to integrate their components fully.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wines are similar to Merlot if I want to explore?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Try Malbec from Argentina for similar plush fruit character with slightly more structure, or explore Grenache-based wines from the Rhône Valley for comparable softness with different flavor profiles. Sangiovese from Chianti offers medium body and food-friendly acidity like Merlot but with more savory, earthy notes. For a closer match, seek out Carmenère from Chile, which shares Merlot's smooth tannins and rich fruit character while adding distinctive herbal complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive Merlots worth the money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Merlots from top producers like Château Pétrus, Duckhorn, or Leonetti Cellar justify their price through exceptional vineyard sites, low yields, and meticulous winemaking. These wines offer remarkable complexity, age-ability, and concentration that budget bottles cannot match. However, excellent value can be found in the $25-50 range from regions like Washington State's Walla Walla or Bordeaux's satellite appellations, offering 80% of the quality at a fraction of the cost of trophy wines.</p>
